<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-322-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 322 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  May 29 1989 v11 n22 p62(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Databases divide into central servers and local front ends.andO;(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miller, Michael J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The advent of more sophisticated microcomputer technology hasencouraged vendors to view data bases as two distinct parts: thefront-end, which controls on-screen data display and user-datainteraction; and the data base engine, which stores the data andperforms functions like queries, sorts, and indexes.andP;  Front-endproducts are expected within 1989 and 1990.andP;  While they can beconnected to data base servers, most will have their own localdata base engines to benefit users not connected to a network orwho want to maintain data base security.andP;  Several trends areemerging on the use of server-based data bases: medium and largeorganizations will be their primary users; MIS, managers, andusers will jointly decide on which data base server to use; theservers have to be invisible to be successful; data basefront-ends will get better; the success of data base servers willdepend on the vendors' success in attracting good front-ends; andmaintaining server-based data base will be more difficult thanwhat current microcomputer users are used to.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISData Base ServersData Base DesignTrendsAnalysisVendorsFront-End Processors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>